		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//kristof.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/10/13/india-dampens-nepals-celebrations/" data-title="India Dampens Nepal&#8217;s Celebrations" data-description="During the first day of Nepalâs most celebrated holiday, Dashain, many people spent the entire day waiting in line for gas due to Indiaâs informal blockade. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/13/opinion/13kristof_blog_blockade/13kristof_blog_blockade-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/13/opinion/13kristof_blog_blockade/13kristof_blog_blockade-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/13/opinion/13kristof_blog_blockade/13kristof_blog_blockade-blog480.jpg" id="100000003974517" width="480" height="320" alt="An endless line of motorcycles waits for petrol in Kathmandu, Nepal. October 13 marked the first day in almost two weeks that owners of private vehicles could purchase fuel in the capital."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">An endless line of motorcycles waits for petrol in Kathmandu, Nepal. October 13 marked the first day in almost two weeks that owners of private vehicles could purchase fuel in the capital.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Austin Meyer</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="gmail_quote">
<div dir="ltr">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">KATHMANDU, Nepal â October 13 marked the first day of Nepalâs most celebrated holiday, Dashain. During this 15-day festival, people are supposed to be joyous, but instead, many Nepalis spent the entire day waiting in line for gas.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Due to an unofficial blockade imposed by India on its northeastern border that has restricted supplies like fuel to Nepal, a time of year meant for celebration has a very different feel.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe have seen some rehab after the earthquake, but now it seems we have been pushed further back,â says Dr. Sanduk Ruit, an ophthalmologist living in Kathmandu. âThe economy has gone down and people are suffering.â<br />
<span id="more-13284"></span><br />
Traveling around Nepal, there is very little traffic on the roads. There are unbelievable lines of vehicles waiting for gas, with wait times up to <a href="//www.myrepublica.com/society/story/29189/nepalis-adapt-to-fuel-shortage-by-carpooling-riding-bikes.html" target="_blank">27 hours</a>. Driving around town, you see people waving their hands trying to hitch rides. Nearly all of Nepalâs fuelÂ â aviation fuel, petrol, diesel and cooking gas â comes from India.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When I arrived in Nepal to witness cataract surgeries transform the lives of Nepalese citizens, I had so much joy. People would go from being blind to having 20/20 vision; destruction to restoration in a matter of minutes. It&#8217;s a stark and redemptive contrast to the earthquake destruction that devastated Nepal and has left its infrastructure, economy and people crippled for far too long.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">However, even in a hospital where sight-restoring miracles were taking place, the stress of the blockade was palpable.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âItâs not easy to live here when we are so dependent on India,â said 21-year-old Amit Lama. âNow everything is expensive. Vegetables, fruit and petrol.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Cataract surgeons Dr. Ruit and Dr. Geoffrey Tabin, who set up the <a href="//www.cureblindness.org/">Himalayan Cataract Project</a> camp, said even the number of patients who showed up to have their blindness cured was much lower than expected because people did not have the petrol needed to travel long distances.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">India and Nepalâs friendship is one that reaches back centuries ago. From the marriage of the Indian god Rama to Sita in Nepal, to Buddhaâs birth in Nepal and enlightenment in India. From the 1950 Treaty of Peace and Friendship to the laborers from Bihar and Uttar Pradesh who work all across Nepal.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So whatâs the deal with the sudden hostility and blockade? Hereâs the quick synopsis. Stay with me.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On September 20, Nepal adopted a new constitution that has caused lots of turmoil. The Indian government led by the Hindu-nationalist BJP party is not happy because Nepal, a Hindu-majority, passed a secular constitution. Residents of Nepal&#8217;s southern plains bordering India, known as Madhesis, who have close familial, economic and cultural ties to India, are also not pleased because they feel under-represented.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In apparent retaliation, the Indian government has restricted commercial vehicles entering into Nepal. Meanwhile, Madhesis have staged protests against the constitution at the border that have resulted in dozens of deaths in the last several weeks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">India denies blockading Nepal and says that vehicles are being restricted because of the danger inside the Nepalese border.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThis is really a different chapter in the history of Nepal, and we are seeing different behavior in the history in India,â said Dr. Ruit. âIt has put a lot of hurt on a large number of Nepalis and this hurt feeling is going to remain.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But even though Indiaâs ties to Nepal seem to be tearing, there is a solidarity within the mountainous nation of nearly 30 million that is truly admirable.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âPeople see this as a big country in the south trying to bully us,â said Subhash Ghimire, editor in chief of one of Nepalâs largest newspapers. âThe general population thinks we should stand up to India. People are together on this.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In response to the petrol shortage a Facebook group called <a href="https://www.facebook.com/groups/183696891965171/" target="_blank">Carpool Kathmandu</a> started and has nearly 100,000 members sharing rides. To organize rides, group members create posts with the hashtags #offer #ask #carpoolstory or #filled.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI truly believe we moved a step towards a better society in the last few days with the spirit of sharing kindness and hospitality to complete strangers in this time of need,â posts Manish Shrestha, one of the creators of the Carpool Kathmandu group.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As the first night of the Dashain festival ends, many remain in Kathmandu unable to travel home. For a country in desperate need of something to celebrate, I just hope the blockade ends soon.</p>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text"><em>Austin Meyer is the winner of Nicholas Kristofâs 2015 Win-a-Trip contest.</em></p>
	</div>
